'''Philip Joseph Marchildon''', aka '''Philip "Babe" Marchildon''' (October 25, 1913 &ndash; January 10, 1997) was a Canadian [[Major League Baseball]] [[pitcher]].

Born in [[Penetanguishene, Ontario]], Marchildon pitched 1,214 [[innings]] with a record of 68 wins and 75 losses and a career [[Earned run average|ERA]] of 3.93 on the [[Philadelphia Athletics]] and the [[Boston Red Sox]] from 1940 to 1942 and from 1945 to 1950.

During World War II he served in the Canadian Air Force as a tail gunner.  He was a prisoner of war for nine months.

Marchildon was inducted into the [[Canadian Baseball Hall of Fame]] in 1983. He died in Toronto in 1997 at age 83.

